  <div class="container">
    <h1 class="page-title">Score methodology</h1>
    <p class="page-lead">
      ACW assigns every project two independent scores: <strong>Availability</strong> (can I use this today?) and <strong>Momentum</strong> (is anyone actively developing it?). This page explains what each score measures, walks through two worked examples, and documents the tier thresholds.
    </p>
    <div class="page-meta">
      <span>Version <strong>2.0</strong></span>
      <span class="meta-sep">·</span>
      <a href="https://github.com/hoseasiu/assistive-commons-watch/blob/main/schema.json">Schema JSON</a>
      <span class="meta-sep">·</span>
      <a href="https://github.com/hoseasiu/assistive-commons-watch/blob/main/_fetchers/scoring.py">Scoring source</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ── Main content ── -->
<main id="main-content">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="content-body">

      <!-- ── Left: prose + examples ── -->
      <div class="prose">

        <h2>Why two scores?</h2>
        <p>
          A single composite score creates misleading results when a project's health looks
          different across these two dimensions. A well-documented, freely downloadable font
          with no recent commits is not "at risk" — it is complete. Conversely, an actively
          developed hardware project with no build docs or release artifacts is not "healthy"
          just because its commit graph is busy.
        </p>
        <p>
          Showing Availability and Momentum separately lets visitors apply their own judgment.
          Someone deploying a tool in a clinical context will weight Momentum heavily. Someone
          looking for a font to install today mostly cares about Availability.
        </p>
        <p>The two scores are never added together or averaged into a single number.</p>

        <h2>Availability (1–5)</h2>

        <div class="score-card" style="margin:0 0 20px">
          <div class="score-card-question">Can someone get value from this project right now?</div>
        </div>

        <p>
          Availability measures how ready a project is for immediate use or replication. It looks
          at whether the project is downloadable or installable, whether documentation supports
          end users, whether the license permits use, and whether the project meets AT-specific
          trust signals.
        </p>

        <div class="formula-block">
          availability = 0.40 × replicability<br>
                       + 0.30 × at_specific<br>
                       + 0.20 × provenance<br>
                       + 0.10 × maturity_bonus
        </div>

        <table class="dim-table" aria-label="Availability sub-dimensions">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Sub-dimension</th>
              <th>Weight</th>
              <th>What it measures</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td class="dim-name">Replicability</td>
              <td class="dim-weight">40%</td>
              <td>Can someone build, install, or print this? Checks for release artifacts, bill of materials, build doc quality, installation instructions, and pinned dependencies.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="dim-name">AT-specific</td>
              <td class="dim-weight">30%</td>
              <td>Is it centred on disabled users? Checks for end-user documentation, a feedback channel, co-design involvement (Nothing About Us), and known deployed instances.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="dim-name">Provenance</td>
              <td class="dim-weight">20%</td>
              <td>Is the project trustworthy and legally usable? Checks for an open license (OSI-approved, SIL OFL, CC-BY, etc.), associated publication, institutional affiliation, and origin program.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="dim-name">Maturity bonus</td>
              <td class="dim-weight">10%</td>
              <td>Is the project intentionally complete? Applies a bonus when a project is inferred or curated as mature — preventing well-finished projects from being penalised for low activity.</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <table class="tier-table" aria-label="Availability tier labels">
          <thead><tr><th>Label</th><th>Score</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><span class="tier-label">Ready</span></td><td>4.0 – 5.0</td></tr>
            <tr><td><span class="tier-label">Usable</span></td><td>2.5 – 3.9</td></tr>
            <tr><td><span class="tier-label">Limited</span></td><td>1.0 – 2.4</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <h2>Momentum (1–5)</h2>

        <div class="score-card" style="margin:0 0 20px">
          <div class="score-card-question">Is active development, maintenance, or community energy flowing into this project?</div>
        </div>

        <p>
          Momentum measures the level of ongoing human activity around a project. Low Momentum
          is not inherently bad — a mature, complete project may have low Momentum by design.
          High Momentum signals that issues get responses, the codebase is being maintained,
          and contributors are welcome.
        </p>
        <p>
          Momentum is shown as <strong>N/A</strong> for static-platform projects (Instructables,
          Printables, Thingiverse, MyMiniFactory) where the platform exposes no meaningful
          activity signals.
        </p>

        <div class="formula-block">
          momentum = 0.55 × activity<br>
                   + 0.45 × community
        </div>

        <table class="dim-table" aria-label="Momentum sub-dimensions">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Sub-dimension</th>
              <th>Weight</th>
              <th>What it measures</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td class="dim-name">Activity</td>
              <td class="dim-weight">55%</td>
              <td>Is the project being maintained? Looks at days since last commit (or last log entry for Hackaday), issue response rate, and whether a release shipped in the last year.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="dim-name">Community</td>
              <td class="dim-weight">45%</td>
              <td>Is the project welcoming to contributors? Looks for a CONTRIBUTING guide, code of conduct, and issue templates (GitHub); or team size, followers, and build count (Hackaday).</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <table class="tier-table" aria-label="Momentum tier labels">
          <thead><tr><th>Label</th><th>Score</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><span class="tier-label">Active</span></td><td>4.0 – 5.0</td></tr>
            <tr><td><span class="tier-label">Slow</span></td><td>2.5 – 3.9</td></tr>
            <tr><td><span class="tier-label">Quiet</span></td><td>1.0 – 2.4</td></tr>
            <tr><td><span class="tier-label">Quiet (complete)</span></td><td>1.0 – 2.4 and mature — low activity is expected for a finished project</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <h2>Maturity: inferred flag with curator override</h2>
        <p>
          Some projects are intentionally complete: a font reaches its final letterforms, a
          3D-printable hand splint reaches a well-tested design, a firmware reaches a stable
          release with no open bugs. These projects should not be penalised in Availability for
          low Momentum.
        </p>
        <p>
          ACW infers a <code>mature</code> flag when all of the following are true:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>A release artifact is present</li>
          <li><code>build_docs_quality</code> is <code>partial</code> or <code>complete</code></li>
          <li>The license is open (OSI-approved, SIL OFL, CC-BY, CC-BY-SA, or equivalent)</li>
          <li>Last commit is between 90 days and 5 years ago (not brand-new and not stale into Archived territory)</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Curators can override this in the YAML with <code>maturity: mature</code> (force-apply)
          or <code>maturity: active</code> (suppress). When mature, Availability receives a +0.5
          bonus (capped at 5.0), and the Momentum tier label changes to "Quiet (complete)" to
          signal that low activity is expected.
        </p>

        <h2>Tier labels (overall project status)</h2>
        <p>
          In addition to the two scores, each project receives a single status label derived
          from both together. This is used in browse filters and cards. First matching rule wins:
        </p>

        <table class="tier-table" aria-label="Health tier thresholds">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Tier</th>
              <th>Condition (first match wins)</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><span class="tier-swatch" style="background:oklch(0.52 0.14 22)"></span><span class="tier-label">Archived</span></td>
              <td>Activity score = 0 AND last commit more than 3 years ago.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><span class="tier-swatch" style="background:oklch(0.52 0.16 142)"></span><span class="tier-label">Thriving</span></td>
              <td>Availability ≥ 4.0 AND Momentum ≥ 4.0</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><span class="tier-swatch" style="background:oklch(0.50 0.14 245)"></span><span class="tier-label">Stable</span></td>
              <td>Availability ≥ 3.0 AND Momentum ≥ 2.5</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><span class="tier-swatch" style="background:oklch(0.50 0.14 245)"></span><span class="tier-label">Complete</span></td>
              <td>Availability ≥ 3.0 AND mature AND Momentum &lt; 2.5 — intentionally finished, low activity is expected.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><span class="tier-swatch" style="background:oklch(0.72 0.13 83)"></span><span class="tier-label">Dormant</span></td>
              <td>Availability ≥ 3.0 AND Momentum &lt; 2.5 (not mature) — the project is usable but maintenance is unclear.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><span class="tier-swatch" style="background:oklch(0.62 0.17 47)"></span><span class="tier-label">At Risk</span></td>
              <td>Everything else — availability or momentum gaps that need attention.</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <h2>Worked example 1: OptiKey</h2>
        <p>
          OptiKey is a free, open-source on-screen keyboard for Windows controlled by eye
          gaze, head tracking, or a standard mouse. The two-score view explains its status
          precisely: strong Momentum (the maintainer responds and the community is healthy),
          but limited Availability because there are no build docs and the README doesn't
          cover end-to-end usage.
        </p>

        <div class="example-card">
          <div class="example-header">
            <div>
              <div class="example-project-name">OptiKey</div>
              <div class="example-project-desc">Eye-gaze on-screen keyboard · GPL-3.0 · github.com/OptiKey/OptiKey</div>
            </div>
            <span class="example-tier-badge">At Risk</span>
          </div>

          <div class="dim-rows-header">Availability — Can someone use this today?</div>
          <div class="dim-rows">
            <div class="dim-row">
              <div>
                <div class="dim-row-name">Replicability</div>
                <div class="dim-row-weight">weight 0.40</div>
              </div>
              <div class="dim-row-detail">
                Release artifact present → <strong>2.0 pts</strong>.
                No BOM → 0. Build docs quality "none" → 0.
                Dependencies pinned: unknown → 0.
                README has installation but missing usage section → 0 (both required).
              </div>
              <div>
                <div class="dim-row-score">2.0 / 10</div>
                <div class="dim-row-contrib">× 0.40 = 0.80</div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="dim-row">
              <div>
                <div class="dim-row-name">AT-specific</div>
                <div class="dim-row-weight">weight 0.30</div>
              </div>
              <div class="dim-row-detail">
                End-user docs present → <strong>3.0 pts</strong>.
                Feedback channel present → <strong>2.0 pts</strong>.
                "Nothing About Us" involvement: unverified → 0.
                Known deployed instances: unverified → 0.
              </div>
              <div>
                <div class="dim-row-score">5.0 / 10</div>
                <div class="dim-row-contrib">× 0.30 = 1.50</div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="dim-row">
              <div>
                <div class="dim-row-name">Provenance</div>
                <div class="dim-row-weight">weight 0.20</div>
              </div>
              <div class="dim-row-detail">
                GPL-3.0 is an OSI-approved license → <strong>4.0 pts</strong>.
                No publication, no affiliation, no origin program → 0.
              </div>
              <div>
                <div class="dim-row-score">4.0 / 10</div>
                <div class="dim-row-contrib">× 0.20 = 0.80</div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="dim-row">
              <div>
                <div class="dim-row-name">Maturity</div>
                <div class="dim-row-weight">weight 0.10</div>
              </div>
              <div class="dim-row-detail">
                Not inferred mature: build docs quality "none" fails the requirement.
              </div>
              <div>
                <div class="dim-row-score">0 / 10</div>
                <div class="dim-row-contrib">× 0.10 = 0.00</div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="dim-rows-header">Momentum — Is anyone actively developing this?</div>
          <div class="dim-rows">
            <div class="dim-row">
              <div>
                <div class="dim-row-name">Activity</div>
                <div class="dim-row-weight">weight 0.55</div>
              </div>
              <div class="dim-row-detail">
                Last commit was 99 days ago → <strong>5.0 pts</strong>.
                Issue response rate 54% → min(3.0, 0.54 × 3.34) = <strong>1.8 pts</strong>.
                No release in the last year → 0.
              </div>
              <div>
                <div class="dim-row-score">6.8 / 10</div>
                <div class="dim-row-contrib">× 0.55 = 3.74</div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="dim-row">
              <div>
                <div class="dim-row-name">Community</div>
                <div class="dim-row-weight">weight 0.45</div>
              </div>
              <div class="dim-row-detail">
                CONTRIBUTING file → <strong>4.0 pts</strong>.
                Issue templates → <strong>3.0 pts</strong>.
                Code of conduct → <strong>3.0 pts</strong>.
              </div>
              <div>
                <div class="dim-row-score">10.0 / 10</div>
                <div class="dim-row-contrib">× 0.45 = 4.50</div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="example-totals">
            <div class="example-total-block">
              <div class="example-total-label">Availability</div>
              <div class="example-total-score" style="color:oklch(0.62 0.17 47)">2.24 / 5</div>
              <div class="example-total-tier">raw 3.10 → 1 + (3.10/10)×4 = 2.24 · Limited</div>
            </div>
            <div class="example-total-block">
              <div class="example-total-label">Momentum</div>
              <div class="example-total-score" style="color:oklch(0.52 0.16 142)">4.30 / 5</div>
              <div class="example-total-tier">raw 8.24 → 1 + (8.24/10)×4 = 4.30 · Active</div>
            </div>
            <div class="example-total-block">
              <div class="example-total-label">Tier</div>
              <div class="example-total-score" style="color:oklch(0.62 0.17 47); font-size:18px; padding-top:4px">At Risk</div>
              <div class="example-total-tier">Availability &lt; 3.0</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p>
          OptiKey's community health is exemplary — CONTRIBUTING file, code of conduct, and
          issue templates all present, giving it Active Momentum. Its tier is At Risk because
          <strong>Availability is Limited</strong>: there's no bill of materials (expected for
          software), but the README covers installation without end-to-end usage guidance.
          Adding a usage section to the README and pinning dependencies would push Replicability
          from 2.0 to at least 3.0, raising Availability into the Usable band and likely
          promoting the tier to Stable.
        </p>

        <h2>Worked example 2: OpenDyslexic</h2>
        <p>
          OpenDyslexic is an open-source typeface designed to reduce common visual symptoms of
          dyslexia. A completed font is a good illustration of the <strong>Complete</strong>
          tier: high Availability (widely deployed, user-facing, permissively licensed), low
          Momentum (no recent commits — by design for a finished typeface), and the maturity
          bonus correctly recognises that the project is intentionally done.
        </p>

