        <p>
          Without the maturity bonus, OpenDyslexic's raw Availability score would be 5.4/10,
          yielding 3.16/5 — still Usable, but without the Complete tier. The bonus correctly
          recognises that this is a finished, freely deployable artifact. A well-maintained
          font with wide deployment does not need a busy commit graph to be considered healthy.
        </p>

        <h2>Limitations</h2>
        <p>The scores are heuristics, not verdicts. They cannot see:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Hardware quality</strong> — a BOM can exist and still describe a poorly-designed device. We can verify that documentation is present; we cannot verify that it is accurate or safe.</li>
          <li><strong>Documentation in languages other than English</strong> — <code>documentation_languages</code> is tracked as metadata but does not yet affect scoring.</li>
          <li><strong>Actual usability for disabled people</strong> — the Nothing About Us field captures known co-design involvement, but its absence does not mean disabled people were not involved.</li>
          <li><strong>Private forks or deployment</strong> — a project with no public stars could be deployed widely in a hospital system.</li>
          <li><strong>Regulatory or safety certification</strong> — ISO 9999 codes are recorded as metadata but do not factor into scores.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Formula changes will increment <code>SCORING_VERSION</code> and be announced in the changelog.
        </p>

